==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*laiþa-'', from Indo-European ''*aleit-'' ‘sorrow’.

''Germanic cognates:'' Old Frisian [[leed]], Old Saxon [[leþ|lēþ]] (Dutch [[leed]]), Old High German [[leid]] (German [[Leid]]), Old Norse [[leiðr]] (Swedish [[led]]).

''Indo-European cognates:'' Greek [[αλιτρός]], Irish [[liuss]].

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /la:θ/

===Adjective===
'''lāþ'''
# [[loathsome]], [[hateful]], [[unpleasant]], [[evil]]
#:''Leofest on life lað biþ ðænne'': what is dearest in life, shall then be hateful.

===Noun===
'''lāþ''' ''n''
# a person or thing that is evil, hated or unpleasant
#:''Mid lufe ge mid laðe'': with what is pleasant and what is unpleasant.

